<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-329-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 329 020.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  May 1989 v62 n5 p123(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Proprietary board increases weld cell throughput by 15%.andO;(Transimatics Transimate SA-101 2.0 Turbo-Charger)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dersin, Pierre; Labs, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The addition of a Transimatics Transimate SA-101 2.0 Turbo-Chargerhigh-speed digital logic board to a robotic spot-welding cell atthe Genk, Belgium Ford automobile plant has increased throughputby over 15 percent.andP;  The board resides between the robotcontrollers and the welding gun sensors and activators, reducingthe idle times caused by software overhead that is a function ofthe programmed control of several simultaneous tasks.andP;  Some of thesequential logic control tasks performed by the robot controllerare offloaded onto and executed by the Transimate board to savewait times.andP;  Details of the functioning of the board aredescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ford Motor Co. (products).andO;Topic:     Boards-CardsCase StudyApplicationsSpecial-Purpose Boards-CardsSystem DesignControllersAutomobile IndustryRobotsComputer-Integrated Manufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   This simplified diagram shows Fort's spot welding applications.andO;(chart)Time comparison table. (table)Simplified function chart of the weld process. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>